                    CALIFORNIA LEGISLATURE—
                    2025–2026 REGULAR SESSION</font></div><br clear="all"/><span id="bill_house_num"><div style="float: left; width:50%; font-weight: bold; "><span style="text-transform: uppercase; text-align:left;width:50%;"><b>
                Senate Bill
              </b></span></div><div style="float:right; width:50%; text-align:right;"><span style="text-transform: uppercase;"><b>No. 699</b></span></div></span><hr/><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><table style="border-collapse: collapse" cellSpacing="0" align="center" role="presentation"><tbody><tr><td id="bill_authors" align="center"><span style="font-weight:bold;">Introduced by Senator Ochoa Bogh<br/></span></td></tr><tr><td id="bill_intro_date" align="center" class="textcenter"><br/>February 21, 2025</td></tr></tbody></table></div><hr/><br clear="all"/><div id="title"><span style="font-weight:normal;font-size:0.9em;">An act to add Section 9025.5 to the Government Code, relating to the Legislature.</span></div><br clear="all"/><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><h2>LEGISLATIVE COUNSEL'S DIGEST</h2></div><br/><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0"><span id="subject">SB 699, as amended, Ochoa Bogh.
                          Legislature: constitutional course.</span></div><div><span id="digesttext"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Existing law provides for the administration of the constitutional oath of office and seating of Members of the Legislature at the beginning of any regular session of the Legislature. Existing law requires each Member of the Legislature and each designated employee of the Legislature to attend certain orientation courses conducted by the appropriate legislative ethics committees at least once in each biennial session.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">This bill would require<font color="#B30000"><strike> a Member of the Legislature and an employee</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> all Members and employees</i></font> of the Legislature to attend a course regarding the United States Constitution and the California Constitution within 6 months of the convening of
			 a regular session of the Legislature, except as specified. The bill would require the<font color="#B30000"><strike> Joint Rules Committee</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>
			 Legislative Counsel Bureau</i></font> to develop and conduct the course, as specified.</div></span></div><span class="hidden"><h2>Digest Key</h2></span><span id="vote">
      Vote:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">MAJORITY</span>  </span><span id="appropriation">
      Appropriation:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">NO</span>  </span><span id="fiscalcommittee">
      Fiscal Committee:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase"><font color="#B30000"><strike>NO</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>YES</i></font></span>  </span><span id="localprogram">
      Local Program:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">NO</span>  </span></div><hr/><span class="hidden"><h2>Bill Text</h2></span><div id="bill"><div style=" text-transform: uppercase"><h2 style=" text-align: left;">The people of the State of California do enact as follows:</h2><br/></div><div id="s10.6135260563030387"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0" class="ActionLine"><h3 style="font-weight:bold; display:inline;">SECTION 1.</h3> Section 9025.5 is added to the Government Code, to read:</div><div><div id="id_CD8F1C8D-B213-475C-9EDD-1EF6DA54FE82"><div><p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h6 style="display:inline;">9025.5.</h6> (a) Except as provided in subdivision (b),<font color="#B30000"><strike> a Member of the Legislature and an employee of the Legislature</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> all Members and employees of the Legislature</i></font> shall, within six months of the convening of a regular session of the Legislature, attend a course regarding the United States Constitution and the California Constitution.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(b) (1) If a Member of the Legislature assumes their seat after a regular session is convened, the Member shall attend the course within six months of assuming
						their seat.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) If an employee of the Legislature is hired after a regular session is convened, the employee shall attend the course within six months of their date of hire.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(c) The<font color="#B30000"><strike> Joint Rules Committee</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> Legislative Counsel Bureau, in consultation with the Joint Rules Committee,</i></font> shall develop and conduct the course described in subdivision (a). The course shall be at least two hours in length and address<font color="#B30000"><strike> the principles of federalism, preemption, civil rights, and the separation of powers.</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>
						at a minimum the following topics: federalism, preemption, separation of powers, civil rights, the Bill of Rights, state constitutional rights and freedoms, and the roles and responsibilities of the three branches of government at the state and federal levels.</i></font></div></p></div></div></div></div></div></div></body></html>
